// ═══ INTRODUCTION TO MENTAL HEALTH (18-week General Course) ═══
// A plain-English mental health literacy course for students of any subject —
// covering what mental health is, common conditions, building resilience,
// supporting others, and where to find real help. Written for a general
// audience, not clinicians: no diagnosis, no clinical jargon left unexplained,
// and crisis-related content stays informational and supportive rather than
// describing methods or means, in line with safe messaging guidance used in
// real Mental Health First Aid courses.
const MH_UNITS=[
 {id:"mh_m1",n:1,title:"Understanding Mental Health",mins:150,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"What mental health actually means, why it matters for everyone, and the myths that get in the way of talking about it honestly.",
  keyWords:["mental health","mental illness","continuum","stigma","misconceptions"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"What is mental health, really?",p:[
    "Mental health is our emotional, psychological and social well-being — it shapes how we think, feel, and act, how we handle stress, relate to other people, and make decisions. Everyone has mental health, in the same way everyone has physical health; it isn't something only certain people have.",
    "Mental health is not the same as mental illness. Think of it as a continuum, or sliding scale, running from thriving at one end to struggling at the other — everybody moves along this scale throughout life, and being at a difficult point on it doesn't automatically mean someone has a diagnosable disorder."],
    ex:{t:"Example — health, not an on/off switch",b:["A student feeling anxious before exams is on the continuum, not necessarily unwell.","A person managing a diagnosed anxiety disorder is further along that same continuum.","Both deserve care and attention — the continuum has no 'normal' cutoff line."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Why mental health matters for everyone",p:[
    "Good mental health supports every part of life: physical health, learning, relationships, and work. It also changes across the lifespan — a child, a teenager, and an older adult each face different pressures and different needs.",
    "Mental health isn't only personal — it ripples outward. A parent's well-being affects their children, an employee's well-being affects a workplace, and untreated struggles across a population affect a whole society's productivity, health system, and safety."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the ripple effect",b:["A teacher experiencing burnout has less patience and energy for their class.","Their students, in turn, may feel less supported.","One person's mental health genuinely affects the people around them."]}},
   {art:"ethics",h:"Myths, stigma, and reducing discrimination",p:[
    "Common myths include: 'mental illness is rare', 'it's a sign of weakness', or 'people with mental illness are dangerous'. None of these are true — mental health conditions are common, unrelated to personal weakness, and the vast majority of people living with them are never violent.",
    "Stigma is the negative attitude attached to mental illness, and discrimination is acting on that attitude — for example, excluding someone from opportunities because of their diagnosis. Reducing both starts with accurate information and simply talking about mental health as openly as we talk about physical health."],
    ex:{t:"Example — myth vs fact",b:["Myth: 'Depression just means being a bit sad.'","Fact: Depression is a real condition that can affect sleep, energy, concentration and motivation for weeks or months.","Correcting myths like this, one conversation at a time, is how stigma actually shrinks."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write down one mental health myth you've heard before (from media, family, or friends) and the accurate fact that corrects it, using this module as a reference.",
  check:[
   {q:"Mental health is best described as...",o:["Something only some people have","Our emotional, psychological and social well-being, which everyone has","The same thing as mental illness","A fixed trait that never changes"],a:1},
   {q:"The 'mental health continuum' idea means...",o:["You either have a mental illness or you don't, with nothing in between","Well-being moves along a sliding scale, and everyone shifts along it over time","Only adults are on the continuum","The continuum applies only to diagnosed conditions"],a:1},
   {q:"Reducing stigma around mental health starts mainly with...",o:["Avoiding the topic entirely","Accurate information and open conversation","Ignoring anyone who discusses it","Only discussing it with professionals"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m2",n:2,title:"Foundations of Mental Well-being",mins:150,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"The building blocks of well-being, what good mental health looks like day to day, and the many factors that shape it.",
  keyWords:["emotional well-being","psychological well-being","resilience","self-awareness","risk factors"],
  sections:[
   {art:"layers",h:"The many sides of well-being",p:[
    "Mental well-being isn't one single thing — it has emotional (managing and expressing feelings), psychological (a sense of purpose and self-worth), social (connection and belonging), and for many people, spiritual dimensions (meaning, values, and a sense of something larger than themselves).",
    "These dimensions overlap and support each other. Someone might be emotionally steady but feel socially isolated, or spiritually grounded but psychologically unsure of their direction — well-being is rarely all-or-nothing across every dimension at once."]},
   {art:"achieve",h:"What good mental health actually looks like",p:[
    "It shows up as practical, everyday skills: regulating emotions rather than being controlled by them, bouncing back from setbacks (resilience), keeping positive relationships, being self-aware about your own patterns, and making healthy decisions even under pressure.",
    "None of this means never feeling sad, angry, or afraid — good mental health includes feeling the full range of emotions, but generally being able to manage them without them derailing daily life for long periods."],
    ex:{t:"Example — resilience in action",b:["A student fails an important test.","Instead of giving up entirely, they feel disappointed, then ask for help and adjust their study approach.","That recovery process — not the absence of disappointment — is resilience."]}},
   {art:"gap",h:"What shapes a person's mental health",p:[
    "Mental health is influenced by biological factors (genetics, brain chemistry, physical health), psychological factors (personality, coping style, past experiences), environmental factors (living conditions, safety, access to green space), social factors (relationships, support networks, discrimination), and cultural factors (beliefs and norms around emotions and help-seeking).",
    "No single factor decides someone's mental health alone — it's usually a combination, which is exactly why one person's coping strategy doesn't automatically work the same way for someone else."],
    ex:{t:"Example — multiple factors at once",b:["A person facing job insecurity (environmental) may already carry a family history of anxiety (biological).","Strong friendships (social) can help buffer that stress considerably.","Understanding all the layers, not just one, gives a fuller picture."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List the four (or five, including spiritual) components of well-being covered in this module, and write one honest sentence about your own current state in each area.",
  check:[
   {q:"The dimensions of well-being covered in this module include...",o:["Only physical fitness","Emotional, psychological, social and spiritual well-being","Only academic performance","Only financial well-being"],a:1},
   {q:"Good mental health mainly means...",o:["Never feeling negative emotions","Being able to manage the full range of emotions without them derailing daily life for long","Being constantly happy","Avoiding all stress entirely"],a:1},
   {q:"Factors influencing mental health include...",o:["Only genetics","A combination of biological, psychological, environmental, social and cultural factors","Only personal willpower","Only childhood experiences"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m3",n:3,title:"Common Mental Health Conditions",mins:180,icon:"FlaskConical",
  summary:"A plain-English overview of the mental health conditions people most often encounter — what they involve, and that they're manageable, not shameful.",
  keyWords:["anxiety","depression","bipolar disorder","OCD","PTSD","eating disorders","substance use","schizophrenia"],
  sections:[
   {art:"science",h:"What is a mental disorder?",p:[
    "A mental disorder is a diagnosable condition involving significant disturbance in thinking, emotional regulation, or behaviour, that typically causes real distress or difficulty functioning in daily life. It's diagnosed by trained professionals using established clinical criteria, not by casual observation.",
    "Having a mental disorder is common and treatable, not a personal failing. Around 1 in 4 people worldwide will experience a mental health condition at some point in their life, according to the World Health Organization."]},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Anxiety and depression",p:[
    "Anxiety disorders involve excessive, persistent worry or fear that's hard to control and interferes with daily life — common signs include restlessness, rapid heartbeat, and avoiding situations that trigger fear. Risk factors include genetics, stressful life events, and certain personality traits; management often combines therapy (especially Cognitive Behavioural Therapy), sometimes medication, and lifestyle changes.",
    "Depression involves persistent low mood, loss of interest in previously enjoyable activities, and changes in sleep, appetite or energy, lasting most days for two weeks or more. It can be caused by a mix of biological, psychological and life-event factors, and treatment options include therapy, medication, or a combination, tailored to the individual."]},
   {art:"scale",h:"Stress-related disorders and bipolar disorder",p:[
    "Stress-related disorders develop when overwhelming or traumatic experiences disrupt normal functioning, sometimes leading to conditions like acute stress reaction or adjustment disorder as someone struggles to cope with a specific event or change.",
    "Bipolar disorder involves shifts between depressive episodes (low mood, low energy) and manic or hypomanic episodes (elevated mood, high energy, sometimes risky decision-making). It's a long-term condition typically managed with medication and therapy together, and many people with bipolar disorder lead full, stable lives with the right support."]},
   {art:"control",h:"OCD, PTSD and eating disorders",p:[
    "Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD) involves unwanted, intrusive thoughts (obsessions) and repetitive behaviours or mental acts (compulsions) performed to reduce the distress those thoughts cause — for example, repeated checking or handwashing driven by anxiety, not simple preference for tidiness.",
    "Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) can develop after experiencing or witnessing a traumatic event, involving intrusive memories, avoidance of reminders, and heightened alertness. Eating disorders (like anorexia, bulimia, or binge eating disorder) involve a serious disturbance in eating behaviours and related thoughts about food, weight, or body image, and are genuine medical conditions requiring proper treatment, not simply a matter of willpower."]},
   {art:"crime",h:"Substance use disorders and psychotic disorders",p:[
    "Substance use disorders involve a pattern of using alcohol or other drugs that causes significant impairment or distress — including difficulty cutting down despite wanting to, and continued use despite clear harm. It's classified as a genuine medical condition, often linked with underlying mental health struggles, not a simple lack of discipline.",
    "Schizophrenia and other psychotic disorders can involve hallucinations (sensing things that aren't there), delusions (strongly held false beliefs), and disorganised thinking. These are serious but treatable conditions, and with appropriate treatment many people manage symptoms effectively and live full, independent lives."],
    ex:{t:"Example — treatable, not shameful",b:["A person managing schizophrenia takes prescribed medication and attends regular therapy.","They hold down a job and maintain close friendships, just like anyone managing a long-term physical condition.","Treatment works — the outdated idea that these conditions are hopeless is simply inaccurate."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose one condition from this module and write, in your own simple words, what it is, one risk factor, and one management or treatment option — as if explaining it to a friend who's never heard of it.",
  check:[
   {q:"A mental disorder is diagnosed by...",o:["Casual observation by anyone","Trained professionals using established clinical criteria","Self-diagnosis based on a quiz","Guesswork"],a:1},
   {q:"OCD's compulsions are best described as...",o:["A simple preference for tidiness","Repetitive behaviours performed to reduce distress caused by intrusive thoughts","A form of laziness","Something everyone experiences identically"],a:1},
   {q:"Substance use disorders are best understood as...",o:["A simple lack of discipline","A genuine medical condition, often linked to underlying mental health struggles","Something with no link to mental health at all","Always untreatable"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m4",n:4,title:"Recognizing the Warning Signs",mins:150,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"How mental health struggles actually show up — in feelings, behaviour, the body, and thinking — and when it's time to seek professional help.",
  keyWords:["warning signs","emotional symptoms","behavioral symptoms","physical symptoms","cognitive symptoms"],
  sections:[
   {art:"weigh",h:"Early warning signs",p:[
    "Early warning signs are often subtle changes rather than dramatic ones: withdrawing from friends, a noticeable dip in performance at school or work, or a shift in someone's usual mood or energy that lasts more than a couple of weeks.",
    "The key word is change — a naturally quiet person isn't necessarily struggling, but someone who suddenly becomes withdrawn when they were previously sociable is worth paying attention to."]},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Emotional and behavioral symptoms",p:[
    "Emotional symptoms include persistent sadness, excessive worry, irritability, or feeling numb or disconnected. Behavioral symptoms include changes in sleep or eating patterns, withdrawing from usual activities, increased use of alcohol or drugs, or neglecting personal responsibilities.",
    "These symptoms often show up together — someone feeling persistently low (emotional) may also stop attending activities they used to enjoy (behavioral). Noticing the pattern across both is more informative than a single isolated moment."]},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Physical and cognitive symptoms",p:[
    "Physical symptoms can include fatigue, headaches, changes in appetite or weight, and unexplained aches — mental health struggles often show up in the body, not just the mind. Cognitive symptoms include trouble concentrating, indecisiveness, and negative or repetitive thought patterns.",
    "These physical and cognitive signs are sometimes the first ones people notice in themselves, even before they connect them to their emotional state — which is one reason mental health struggles can go unrecognised for a while."]},
   {art:"help",h:"When to seek professional help",p:[
    "It's time to seek professional help when symptoms last more than two weeks, interfere with daily functioning (work, school, relationships), or involve thoughts of self-harm — in any of these cases, reaching out to a doctor, counsellor, or mental health professional is the right next step.",
    "Seeking help early tends to lead to better outcomes than waiting until a crisis point. There is nothing to be ashamed of in reaching out — it is exactly the same as seeing a doctor for a physical symptom that isn't going away on its own."]},
  ],
  activity:"Create a simple table with four columns — Emotional, Behavioral, Physical, Cognitive — and list two example warning signs under each, using this module as your source.",
  check:[
   {q:"An important signal that a change may be a warning sign is...",o:["Any variation in mood at all, however brief","A noticeable, sustained change from someone's usual pattern","Only physical symptoms count","Only symptoms lasting a single day"],a:1},
   {q:"Cognitive symptoms of a mental health struggle can include...",o:["Only physical pain","Trouble concentrating and repetitive negative thought patterns","Only changes in appetite","Only changes in sleep"],a:1},
   {q:"A sensible guideline for seeking professional help is when symptoms...",o:["Last only a single day","Persist more than two weeks or interfere with daily functioning","Never actually require any action","Only occur once a year"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m5",n:5,title:"Stress and Mental Health",mins:150,icon:"Target",
  summary:"What stress actually is, how it affects the body and mind over time, and practical ways to manage it before it turns into burnout.",
  keyWords:["stress","chronic stress","burnout","stress management","coping"],
  sections:[
   {art:"chart",h:"Understanding stress: types and causes",p:[
    "Stress is the body's natural response to a perceived demand or threat — it isn't inherently bad; short bursts of stress (acute stress) can actually sharpen focus and performance. Problems arise with chronic stress: ongoing pressure without enough recovery time in between.",
    "Common causes include work or academic pressure, financial worries, relationship difficulties, major life changes, and even positive events like a wedding or a new job, since any significant change asks the body and mind to adapt."]},
   {art:"weigh",h:"The effects of chronic stress",p:[
    "Chronic stress can affect sleep, digestion, the immune system, and cardiovascular health over time, and is strongly linked to anxiety and depression. It can also affect concentration, memory, and patience in relationships, since a body constantly on alert has fewer resources left for calm thinking.",
    "Because chronic stress builds gradually, it's often normalised — someone may not realise how stressed they've become until symptoms (poor sleep, irritability, exhaustion) have been present for a long time."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the slow build of chronic stress",b:["A student takes on a heavy course load alongside a part-time job.","Weeks pass with little rest, and they start sleeping poorly and snapping at friends.","They hadn't noticed the gradual buildup until a friend pointed out how different they seemed."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Managing stress and preventing burnout",p:[
    "Effective stress management includes regular physical activity, adequate sleep, relaxation techniques (like deep breathing or mindfulness), talking to someone you trust, and realistic time management that builds in actual rest, not just fewer tasks.",
    "Burnout is what happens when chronic stress goes unmanaged for too long — a state of physical and emotional exhaustion, cynicism, and reduced sense of accomplishment. Preventing it means noticing early warning signs and adjusting workload or support before reaching that point, rather than pushing through indefinitely."],
    ex:{t:"Example — catching burnout early",b:["An employee notices they've stopped caring about work they used to enjoy.","Instead of ignoring it, they talk to their manager about workload and take a short break.","Addressing it early prevented a full burnout crisis later."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Identify one current source of stress in your own life, name whether it's acute or chronic, and write one specific management technique from this module you will actually try this week.",
  check:[
   {q:"Short bursts of acute stress can actually...",o:["Never have any positive effect","Sharpen focus and performance in the short term","Always cause permanent harm","Only affect physical health, never mental"],a:1},
   {q:"Chronic stress is best described as...",o:["A single stressful event with no lasting effect","Ongoing pressure without enough recovery time in between","Something that only affects athletes","Always caused by financial problems specifically"],a:1},
   {q:"Burnout is best understood as...",o:["A sign of poor character","The result of chronic stress going unmanaged for too long, causing exhaustion and cynicism","Something that only happens to older adults","Completely unrelated to workload"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m6",n:6,title:"Building Positive Mental Health",mins:150,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"The everyday, practical habits — movement, food, sleep, and how you structure your time — that genuinely support mental well-being.",
  keyWords:["exercise","nutrition","sleep","time management","work-life balance"],
  sections:[
   {art:"achieve",h:"Movement, food, and the brain",p:[
    "Regular physical activity is one of the most consistently proven ways to improve mood, reduce anxiety, and support better sleep — even modest amounts, like a 20-30 minute walk most days, make a measurable difference.",
    "Nutrition also affects brain health: a generally balanced diet with regular meals supports stable energy and mood, while skipping meals or relying heavily on caffeine and sugar can contribute to mood swings and poor concentration."]},
   {art:"steps",h:"Sleep and mental wellness",p:[
    "Sleep and mental health influence each other in both directions: poor sleep worsens mood, concentration, and stress tolerance, while anxiety or depression can also make sleep harder to get. Adults generally need 7-9 hours a night, and consistent sleep and wake times help more than people expect.",
    "Simple sleep habits — a consistent bedtime, limiting screens before bed, and a calm wind-down routine — are often more effective than they sound, precisely because so many people neglect the basics rather than needing anything complicated."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the sleep-mood connection",b:["A student stays up late scrolling their phone most nights.","They notice they feel more irritable and less focused during the day.","Improving sleep habits alone often improves mood noticeably within a couple of weeks."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"Time management and work-life balance",p:[
    "Good time management isn't just about productivity — it's a mental health tool, since feeling constantly behind or overwhelmed is itself a major source of stress. Prioritising tasks, breaking large tasks into smaller steps, and building in real breaks all help.",
    "Work-life balance means protecting time for rest, relationships, and activities unrelated to work or study — not as a luxury, but as something that actually sustains performance and well-being over the long run, rather than working against it."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Pick one habit from this module (movement, nutrition, sleep, or time management) that you personally could improve, and write a specific, realistic plan to change it over the next week.",
  check:[
   {q:"Regular physical activity is linked to...",o:["No measurable effect on mood","Improved mood, reduced anxiety, and better sleep","Only physical benefits, with no mental health impact","Increased stress in most people"],a:1},
   {q:"The relationship between sleep and mental health is best described as...",o:["One-directional — only sleep affects mood","Bidirectional — poor sleep worsens mood, and mood struggles can worsen sleep","Nonexistent","Only relevant to children"],a:1},
   {q:"Work-life balance is best understood as...",o:["An unnecessary luxury","Protecting time for rest and relationships in a way that actually sustains long-term well-being","Working as many hours as possible","Irrelevant to mental health"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m7",n:7,title:"Emotional Intelligence",mins:150,icon:"Users",
  summary:"Understanding and managing your own emotions, reading other people accurately, and using both to build genuinely healthy relationships.",
  keyWords:["emotional intelligence","self-awareness","self-regulation","empathy","social skills"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"Understanding emotions and self-awareness",p:[
    "Emotional intelligence is the ability to recognise, understand and manage emotions — both your own and other people's. Self-awareness, the first building block, means noticing what you're feeling and why, rather than reacting automatically without realising what's driving the reaction.",
    "Building self-awareness is a practical skill, not a fixed trait: simply pausing to name an emotion ('I'm feeling frustrated right now') before reacting is a genuinely effective starting habit that improves with practice."]},
   {art:"control",h:"Self-regulation and empathy",p:[
    "Self-regulation means managing your emotional responses rather than being controlled by them — for example, taking a breath before responding in anger, rather than reacting instantly. It doesn't mean suppressing emotions, but choosing how to express them constructively.",
    "Empathy is the ability to understand and share another person's feelings. It's built by genuinely listening, imagining a situation from someone else's perspective, and resisting the urge to immediately judge or fix before fully understanding what they're actually experiencing."],
    ex:{t:"Example — self-regulation in a real moment",b:["A colleague makes a mistake that affects your work.","Instead of reacting immediately with anger, you pause, notice the frustration, and respond calmly once you've thought it through.","The emotion was real; the response was chosen, not automatic."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Social skills and healthy relationships",p:[
    "Strong social skills — clear communication, active listening, and resolving conflict respectfully — combine self-awareness, self-regulation and empathy into real-world interaction. These skills are learnable, and improve significantly with deliberate practice.",
    "Healthy relationships are built on these same foundations: mutual respect, honest communication, and the ability to manage disagreements without either party's emotional reactions taking over the conversation entirely."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Recall one recent disagreement or tense moment. Write down what emotion you were actually feeling, and one thing you could have done differently using self-regulation or empathy from this module.",
  check:[
   {q:"Emotional intelligence is best defined as...",o:["Suppressing all emotions at all times","The ability to recognise, understand and manage emotions in yourself and others","Being naturally unemotional","Only relevant in the workplace"],a:1},
   {q:"Self-regulation mainly means...",o:["Never feeling emotions","Managing your emotional response constructively rather than being controlled by it","Ignoring your feelings entirely","Expressing every emotion immediately and without restraint"],a:1},
   {q:"Empathy is best built through...",o:["Assuming you already understand someone else's perspective","Genuine listening and imagining a situation from another person's perspective","Immediately offering solutions before listening","Avoiding emotional topics altogether"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m8",n:8,title:"Mental Health Across Different Life Stages",mins:150,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"How mental health needs and challenges shift from childhood through older age — and why one-size-fits-all support rarely works.",
  keyWords:["children","adolescents","young adults","adults","older adults"],
  sections:[
   {art:"family",h:"Childhood and adolescence",p:[
    "Children's mental health is closely tied to stability, secure attachment to caregivers, and consistent routines; common challenges include anxiety, behavioural difficulties, and the effects of adverse experiences at home or school. Early support has a lasting protective effect.",
    "Adolescence brings rapid brain development, identity formation, and increased social and academic pressure, which is why this stage sees a rise in conditions like anxiety, depression, and eating disorders. Peer relationships and social media use also become significant influences during these years."]},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Young adults and adults",p:[
    "Young adults navigate major transitions — further study, first jobs, independent living, and new relationships — often while support systems from home become less immediate. This stage carries elevated risk for anxiety, depression and substance use, partly due to instability and uncertainty during transition.",
    "Adulthood brings its own pressures: career demands, parenting, financial responsibility, and often caring for ageing parents simultaneously. Mental health at this stage is frequently affected by the cumulative load of competing responsibilities rather than any single cause."]},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Older adults",p:[
    "Older adults face distinct mental health considerations: loss of loved ones, retirement and role changes, physical health decline, and sometimes isolation, all of which can contribute to depression or anxiety that is too often dismissed as 'just aging' rather than recognised and treated.",
    "Cognitive changes, including dementia in some cases, add complexity, but ordinary depression and anxiety in older adults remain highly treatable and should never be assumed to be a normal, untreatable part of getting older."],
    ex:{t:"Example — not 'just aging'",b:["An older adult becomes withdrawn and loses interest in activities after retirement.","Family assumes this is simply 'slowing down with age'.","In fact, it may be treatable depression — assuming it's normal ageing can delay real help."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose one life stage from this module (not your own current stage) and write three mental health considerations specific to that stage, in your own words.",
  check:[
   {q:"A key factor in children's mental health is...",o:["Academic pressure alone","Stability, secure attachment, and consistent routines","Total independence from caregivers","Peer pressure exclusively"],a:1},
   {q:"Mental health risk tends to rise during adolescence partly due to...",o:["No real biological changes at all","Rapid brain development, identity formation, and increased social/academic pressure","A complete absence of any risk factors","Only genetic factors, with no environmental influence"],a:1},
   {q:"Depression in older adults should be treated as...",o:["An unavoidable, untreatable part of aging","A genuine, treatable condition, not simply 'normal aging'","Something that never actually occurs in this age group","Only a physical health issue, unrelated to mental health"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m9",n:9,title:"Mental Health in Different Settings",mins:150,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"How schools, workplaces, families, and communities each shape mental health, for better or worse — and what supportive settings look like.",
  keyWords:["schools","workplace","families","communities","religious organizations"],
  sections:[
   {art:"school",h:"Schools and universities",p:[
    "Schools and universities are major mental health environments for young people, shaping self-esteem, social belonging, and stress levels through academic pressure, relationships with peers and teachers, and the availability (or absence) of counselling support.",
    "Supportive educational settings actively build mental health literacy, offer accessible counselling, and create cultures where struggling students feel safe asking for help rather than fearing judgment or academic penalty for doing so."]},
   {art:"agency",h:"Workplace and families",p:[
    "Workplaces affect mental health through workload, management style, job security, and workplace culture — supportive employers who take mental health seriously see real benefits in retention and performance, not just employee well-being for its own sake.",
    "Families remain one of the most powerful influences on mental health across every life stage — providing (or sometimes failing to provide) emotional support, stability, and a safe space to be honest about struggles without fear of judgment or rejection."]},
   {art:"culture",h:"Communities and religious organizations",p:[
    "Communities shape mental health through social connection, safety, access to resources, and shared identity — strong community ties are consistently linked to better mental health outcomes, while isolation is a significant risk factor.",
    "Religious and faith-based organisations often provide meaning, community, and practical support networks for many people, and increasingly play a role in mental health awareness and referral, sometimes bridging gaps where formal mental health services are limited."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Pick one setting from this module that's most relevant to your own life right now (school, workplace, family, or community) and describe one thing that setting currently does well for your mental health, and one thing it could improve.",
  check:[
   {q:"A supportive school environment is characterised by...",o:["Strict silence around any mental health topic","Active mental health literacy and accessible counselling support","Academic pressure with no support structures","Complete absence of any counselling services"],a:1},
   {q:"Supportive employers who take mental health seriously typically see...",o:["No measurable benefit at all","Real benefits in retention and performance, alongside employee well-being","Only increased costs with no upside","Decreased productivity"],a:1},
   {q:"Community social connection is linked to...",o:["Worse mental health outcomes","Better mental health outcomes, while isolation is a significant risk factor","No connection to mental health whatsoever","Only physical health benefits"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m10",n:10,title:"Supporting Someone with Mental Health Challenges",mins:150,icon:"Users",
  summary:"Practical, respectful ways to recognise when someone needs support, actually listen well, and help them find professional care — plus what to avoid saying.",
  keyWords:["active listening","emotional support","professional help","crisis response"],
  sections:[
   {art:"weigh",h:"Recognising someone in need, and active listening",p:[
    "Recognising someone in need often means noticing the same warning signs covered in Module 4 — withdrawal, mood changes, or behaviour shifts — combined with your own knowledge of what's normal for that specific person.",
    "Active listening means giving someone your full attention, not interrupting, not immediately problem-solving, and reflecting back what you've heard to show genuine understanding, rather than waiting for your turn to speak or share your own similar experience."],
    ex:{t:"Example — active listening vs. quick-fixing",b:["A friend says, 'I've just been feeling really overwhelmed lately.'","A quick-fix response: 'Just try to relax more.'","An active-listening response: 'That sounds really hard — do you want to tell me more about what's been going on?'"]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Providing emotional support",p:[
    "Emotional support means validating someone's feelings ('that sounds really difficult') rather than minimising them ('it's not that bad'), being genuinely present without judgment, and following up over time rather than treating one conversation as the whole solution.",
    "You don't need to have answers or be a trained counsellor to provide meaningful support — often, simply being present, patient, and non-judgmental is exactly what helps most in the moment."]},
   {art:"talk",h:"Encouraging professional help, and what not to say",p:[
    "Encouraging professional help works best when it's framed with care, not pressure — offering to help find a counsellor, or offering to go with someone to a first appointment, rather than issuing an ultimatum. Respect that the decision ultimately belongs to them, while continuing to express care.",
    "Unhelpful things to avoid saying include 'just snap out of it', 'other people have it worse', or 'you're overreacting' — all of these minimise real struggles and can make someone less likely to open up again in future."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reframing an unhelpful response",b:["Unhelpful: 'Just stop worrying so much, it's not a big deal.'","Better: 'I can see this is really weighing on you — have you thought about talking to someone about it?'","The second response supports without dismissing the person's actual experience."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Crisis response",p:[
    "If someone appears to be in immediate danger to themselves or others, stay calm, stay with them (or ensure someone else does), remove any immediate means of harm if it's safe to do so, and contact emergency services or a crisis line without delay — this is not a situation to handle entirely alone.",
    "After a crisis has passed, continued follow-up and connecting the person with ongoing professional support matters just as much as the immediate response — a crisis moment is often the beginning of a longer recovery process, not a single event with a single fix."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Write out, in your own words, what you would actually say to a friend who told you they were feeling persistently overwhelmed — using the active listening and support principles from this module, and avoiding the 'what not to say' examples.",
  check:[
   {q:"Active listening mainly involves...",o:["Interrupting to offer quick solutions","Giving full attention, not interrupting, and reflecting back what you've heard","Sharing your own similar story immediately","Waiting silently without any response at all"],a:1},
   {q:"An example of an unhelpful thing to say to someone struggling is...",o:["'That sounds really difficult.'","'Just snap out of it.'","'Do you want to talk more about it?'","'I'm here for you.'"],a:1},
   {q:"If someone appears to be in immediate danger, the appropriate response is to...",o:["Leave them alone to calm down by themselves","Stay calm, stay with them, and contact emergency services or a crisis line without delay","Wait a few days to see if it passes","Handle it entirely alone without involving anyone else"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m11",n:11,title:"Mental Health Promotion",mins:120,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"Moving from individual support to bigger-picture change — raising awareness, advocating for better systems, and building genuinely supportive environments.",
  keyWords:["awareness","advocacy","community education","supportive environments","stigma reduction"],
  sections:[
   {art:"global",h:"Awareness and advocacy",p:[
    "Mental health awareness means helping people recognise and understand mental health issues accurately — through campaigns, education, and simply everyday honest conversation. Advocacy goes a step further: actively pushing for better policies, funding, and access to care.",
    "Both roles matter and don't require special credentials — sharing accurate information, challenging a stigmatising comment when you hear one, or supporting mental health initiatives at school or work are all genuine forms of promotion and advocacy."]},
   {art:"school",h:"Community education and supportive environments",p:[
    "Community education means bringing accurate mental health information to schools, workplaces, and public spaces, so that recognising signs and knowing how to respond isn't limited to specialists. Creating supportive environments means building physical and social spaces where people feel safe discussing struggles without fear of judgment or consequence.",
    "Small, concrete actions build supportive environments over time: a workplace normalising mental health days, a school training staff in basic mental health awareness, or a community group openly discussing well-being rather than treating it as taboo."]},
   {art:"ethics",h:"Reducing stigma",p:[
    "Reducing stigma is an ongoing, collective effort — it requires correcting myths (Module 1), using respectful, person-first language ('a person with schizophrenia' rather than 'a schizophrenic'), and treating mental health conditions with the same seriousness and compassion given to physical illness.",
    "Real progress happens gradually, through repeated small actions across many people, rather than a single campaign — which is exactly why individual conversations and everyday behaviour matter just as much as large public initiatives."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Identify one small, realistic action you could personally take this month to promote mental health awareness or reduce stigma in your own school, workplace, or community.",
  check:[
   {q:"Mental health advocacy is best described as...",o:["Only something professionals can do","Actively pushing for better policies, funding, and access to care","Illegal without special credentials","Unrelated to awareness efforts"],a:1},
   {q:"Person-first language (like 'a person with schizophrenia') is used mainly to...",o:["Make sentences longer for no reason","Treat the person as more than just their diagnosis, reducing stigma","Confuse listeners intentionally","Replace the need for accurate information"],a:1},
   {q:"Reducing stigma is best achieved through...",o:["A single large campaign with no ongoing effort","Repeated small actions and honest conversations across many people over time","Avoiding the topic to prevent discomfort","Ignoring myths rather than correcting them"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m12",n:12,title:"Professional Mental Health Care",mins:120,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"Who actually provides mental health care, how their roles differ, and the main treatment approaches used today.",
  keyWords:["psychologists","psychiatrists","counsellors","CBT","psychotherapy","medication"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"Who's who: mental health professionals",p:[
    "Psychologists study behaviour and mental processes and provide therapy and psychological assessment, but (in most places) cannot prescribe medication. Psychiatrists are medical doctors who specialise in mental health and can prescribe and manage medication alongside other treatment.",
    "Counsellors provide talk-based support, often for specific issues or shorter-term concerns; clinical social workers combine therapeutic support with practical help navigating services and resources; and occupational therapists help people build or rebuild skills for daily functioning, particularly relevant after a significant mental health episode."]},
   {art:"mark",h:"Types of treatment",p:[
    "Counselling and psychotherapy involve talking through difficulties with a trained professional, using structured approaches to build understanding and change unhelpful patterns. Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT), one of the most researched approaches, focuses specifically on identifying and changing unhelpful thought and behaviour patterns.",
    "Medication, prescribed and monitored by a psychiatrist or qualified doctor, can help manage symptoms for many conditions, often alongside therapy rather than instead of it. Group therapy brings people with similar experiences together, offering both professional guidance and peer support at the same time."],
    ex:{t:"Example — combining approaches",b:["A person with moderate depression works with a psychiatrist who prescribes medication.","They also attend weekly CBT sessions with a psychologist to build coping skills.","Combining treatment types is common and often more effective than relying on just one."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write a short paragraph explaining, in your own words, the difference between a psychologist and a psychiatrist, and one situation where each might be the right person to see.",
  check:[
   {q:"The main difference between psychologists and psychiatrists is that psychiatrists...",o:["Cannot provide any therapy at all","Are medical doctors who can prescribe and manage medication","Only work with children","Never receive specialised mental health training"],a:1},
   {q:"Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT) mainly focuses on...",o:["Only medication management","Identifying and changing unhelpful thought and behaviour patterns","Group activities exclusively","Physical exercise routines"],a:1},
   {q:"Group therapy offers a distinct benefit because it combines...",o:["Only peer support, with no professional guidance","Professional guidance and peer support from people with similar experiences at the same time","Only medication, with no talking involved","Isolation from others facing similar struggles"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m13",n:13,title:"Mental Health and Digital Well-being",mins:120,icon:"Video",
  summary:"How social media, screen time, and online life affect mental health — and building healthier digital habits without demonising technology entirely.",
  keyWords:["social media","screen time","cyberbullying","digital habits"],
  sections:[
   {art:"global",h:"Social media and screen time",p:[
    "Social media can support connection and community, but heavy or passive use (scrolling without real interaction) is linked to increased anxiety, lower self-esteem, and poorer sleep, particularly through social comparison — measuring your own life against other people's carefully curated highlights.",
    "Screen time itself isn't automatically harmful; what matters most is what the time replaces (sleep, exercise, face-to-face connection) and how it's used (passive scrolling versus meaningful interaction or genuinely enjoyable content)."]},
   {art:"control",h:"Cyberbullying",p:[
    "Cyberbullying is repeated, intentional harassment or harm carried out through digital platforms — it can feel inescapable compared to traditional bullying, since it can follow someone home and continue at any hour, and often happens in front of a wide, silent audience.",
    "Responding to cyberbullying, whether experiencing or witnessing it, involves not engaging with or forwarding harmful content, documenting evidence, reporting it on the platform, and involving a trusted adult or authority rather than handling serious cases entirely alone."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a supportive response to cyberbullying",b:["A student sees a classmate being targeted in a group chat.","Instead of staying silent or joining in, they screenshot the messages and tell a trusted teacher.","Reporting rather than ignoring often stops the behaviour faster and protects the person being targeted."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Healthy digital habits and technology for wellness",p:[
    "Healthy digital habits include setting specific times to check devices rather than constantly, turning off non-essential notifications, and keeping screens out of the bedroom to protect sleep. Curating your feed toward genuinely positive, useful content also matters more than most people realise.",
    "Technology can also actively support mental wellness — meditation and mindfulness apps, mood-tracking tools, and access to online therapy or support communities are all examples of digital tools working for well-being rather than against it, when used intentionally."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Track your own screen time for one day (most phones show this automatically), and identify one specific, realistic change you could make to your digital habits based on this module.",
  check:[
   {q:"Heavy, passive social media use is particularly linked to...",o:["Improved self-esteem in all cases","Increased anxiety and lower self-esteem, often through social comparison","No effect on mental health whatsoever","Only physical health effects"],a:1},
   {q:"A recommended response to witnessing cyberbullying is to...",o:["Ignore it completely, since it's not your business","Avoid engaging with harmful content and report it, involving a trusted adult if serious","Forward the content to more people to raise awareness","Respond to the bully directly with equal hostility"],a:1},
   {q:"Technology's role in mental wellness can include...",o:["Only negative effects, with no positive use","Meditation apps, mood-tracking tools, and access to online therapy or support communities","Nothing — technology is unrelated to wellness","Only replacing all in-person therapy"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m14",n:14,title:"Suicide Prevention and Crisis Intervention",mins:150,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"A sensitive but essential module on recognising risk, understanding protective factors, and responding supportively to someone in crisis — always by connecting them to real help.",
  keyWords:["risk factors","warning signs","protective factors","crisis response","referral pathways"],
  sections:[
   {art:"weigh",h:"Understanding suicide and risk factors",p:[
    "Suicide is a leading cause of death worldwide, and understanding it clearly, without stigma or judgment, is a core part of mental health literacy. It is generally the result of overwhelming pain combined with a sense that there's no other way out — not a sudden, causeless decision, and almost always connected to treatable underlying struggles.",
    "Risk factors include a prior mental health condition (especially depression), previous attempts, significant loss or trauma, social isolation, substance use, and access to lethal means. Having risk factors does not mean someone will act on them — but it does mean extra care and attention are warranted."]},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Warning signs and protective factors",p:[
    "Warning signs can include talking about wanting to die or feeling like a burden, withdrawing from others, giving away possessions, a sudden and unexplained sense of calm after a period of depression, and increased substance use. Any of these deserve a direct, caring conversation, not silence.",
    "Protective factors — things that reduce risk — include strong social connections, access to mental health care, a sense of purpose, and problem-solving skills. Strengthening these protective factors, for yourself or someone you're supporting, is genuinely meaningful prevention work."]},
   {art:"talk",h:"Responding to someone in crisis",p:[
    "If you're worried about someone, ask directly and calmly whether they are thinking about suicide — asking does not plant the idea or increase risk; it opens the door to honest conversation and shows you take their pain seriously.",
    "Listen without judgment, stay with them or ensure they aren't left alone, and help them connect to professional support or a crisis line immediately. This is a moment to involve trained help, not something to manage entirely alone as a friend or family member — connecting someone to the right support is the most valuable thing you can do."],
  },
   {art:"control",h:"Referral pathways",p:[
    "Referral pathways include crisis helplines (many countries have a dedicated national suicide prevention or crisis line, often available by phone or text), emergency services for immediate danger, a doctor or mental health professional for ongoing care, and school or workplace counsellors as a first point of contact.",
    "Following up after connecting someone to help matters — checking in over the following days and weeks shows continued care, and recovery from a crisis is typically an ongoing process supported by consistent professional care, not a single conversation or a single hotline call."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Without needing to share anything personal, write down (or look up) the crisis helpline number available in your own country, and note where you'd direct a friend to find professional mental health support locally.",
  check:[
   {q:"Asking someone directly whether they are thinking about suicide...",o:["Increases their risk by planting the idea","Does not increase risk, and can open the door to an honest, caring conversation","Should always be avoided","Is only appropriate for professionals to ask"],a:1},
   {q:"Protective factors that reduce suicide risk include...",o:["Isolation and lack of support","Strong social connections, access to mental health care, and a sense of purpose","Avoiding all conversation about feelings","Increased substance use"],a:1},
   {q:"If someone tells you they are in crisis, the appropriate response is to...",o:["Handle it alone and keep it completely private from any professional","Listen without judgment and help connect them to professional support or a crisis line right away","Change the subject to avoid discomfort","Wait to see if the feeling passes on its own before doing anything"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m15",n:15,title:"Mental Health First Aid",mins:120,icon:"Target",
  summary:"A practical action framework for supporting someone in distress, and how to respond when a situation becomes an emergency.",
  keyWords:["ALGEE","mental health first aid","emergency response","supporting distress"],
  sections:[
   {art:"steps",h:"What is Mental Health First Aid, and the ALGEE plan?",p:[
    "Mental Health First Aid is the help offered to a person experiencing a mental health problem or crisis, before professional help is available or arranged — in the same spirit as physical first aid, it's not a substitute for professional treatment, but a bridge to it.",
    "A widely used framework is ALGEE: Approach the person, assess and assist with any crisis; Listen non-judgmentally; Give reassurance and information; Encourage appropriate professional help; and Encourage other supports (friends, family, community resources)."]},
   {art:"help",h:"Supporting someone in distress",p:[
    "Approach calmly, in a private setting if possible, and let the person know you've noticed something seems difficult for them, without making assumptions about what's wrong. Listening non-judgmentally means genuinely hearing them out without interrupting, criticising, or rushing to conclusions.",
    "Giving reassurance means acknowledging that support and effective treatment exist, and that reaching out is a sign of strength rather than weakness — many people hesitate to seek help simply because they've never heard that reassurance clearly stated."]},
   {art:"control",h:"Emergency response",p:[
    "If the situation is an emergency — immediate risk to the person's safety or someone else's — prioritise safety first: stay with them, remove access to immediate means of harm where safely possible, and contact emergency services without delay, rather than attempting to resolve the crisis entirely through conversation alone.",
    "After an emergency has been addressed, continue encouraging ongoing professional support and check in over the following days — Mental Health First Aid is about the immediate bridge to help, but recovery continues well beyond that first moment."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Write out the ALGEE steps from memory, then next to each one, note one specific action you would personally take if applying it to support a friend.",
  check:[
   {q:"Mental Health First Aid is best understood as...",o:["A full replacement for professional treatment","Help offered before professional help is available, acting as a bridge to it","Something only doctors can provide","Irrelevant unless someone is in a full emergency"],a:1},
   {q:"In the ALGEE framework, the 'L' stands for...",o:["Leave the person alone","Listen non-judgmentally","Lecture them on what to do","Locate a professional immediately, skipping conversation"],a:1},
   {q:"In an emergency situation, the first priority is to...",o:["Try to resolve everything through conversation alone","Prioritise safety and contact emergency services without delay","Wait until the person calms down on their own","Avoid involving anyone else"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m16",n:16,title:"Self-Care and Resilience",mins:150,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"What real self-care looks like across different areas of life, how resilience is actually built, and creating a personal wellness plan you'll actually use.",
  keyWords:["self-care","resilience","coping strategies","wellness plan"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"What is self-care?",p:[
    "Self-care means deliberately taking action to protect and support your own well-being — it's not indulgence or selfishness, but a genuine maintenance practice, similar to regular exercise or eating well, that supports your capacity to function and to care for others.",
    "Effective self-care is personal and varies from person to person; what restores one person's energy (quiet time alone) might not work for another (who might recharge through social connection instead)."]},
   {art:"layers",h:"The many types of self-care",p:[
    "Self-care spans several areas: physical (sleep, movement, nutrition), emotional (processing feelings, allowing yourself joy), social (nurturing relationships), spiritual (meaning and values), financial (managing money in a way that reduces stress rather than adding to it), and occupational (maintaining reasonable boundaries and satisfaction at work or school).",
    "A well-rounded self-care approach touches several of these areas, since neglecting one (like financial stress) can undermine progress in another (like emotional well-being), even if that connection isn't always obvious at first."]},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Building resilience and coping strategies",p:[
    "Resilience is built through experience, not avoidance — facing manageable challenges, learning from setbacks, and developing confidence in your own ability to cope, rather than being shielded from every difficulty. Strong relationships, a sense of purpose, and problem-solving skills all strengthen it over time.",
    "Positive coping strategies include talking to someone you trust, physical activity, creative expression, and structured problem-solving. Negative coping strategies — avoidance, substance use, or excessive isolation — may relieve stress briefly but tend to worsen well-being over time."],
    ex:{t:"Example — positive vs negative coping",b:["Facing a stressful week, one person goes for a run and talks to a friend about it (positive coping).","Another person avoids the issue entirely and drinks heavily to numb the stress (negative coping).","The first approach builds resilience over time; the second tends to add new problems on top of the original stress."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Creating a personal wellness plan",p:[
    "A personal wellness plan is a simple, written document listing your own early warning signs, go-to coping strategies, people you can reach out to, and professional resources available if things get harder — written in advance, while you're feeling well, so it's ready when you need it most.",
    "Reviewing and updating this plan periodically keeps it genuinely useful, since what supports your well-being can shift over time as circumstances, relationships, and responsibilities change."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Draft the outline of your own personal wellness plan: one early warning sign to watch for, two coping strategies that genuinely work for you, and one person or resource you would reach out to if needed.",
  check:[
   {q:"Self-care is best understood as...",o:["Selfish indulgence","A genuine maintenance practice that supports your ability to function and care for others","Something only necessary during a crisis","Identical for every single person"],a:1},
   {q:"Resilience is mainly built through...",o:["Being shielded from every difficulty","Facing manageable challenges and learning from setbacks over time","Avoiding all stress entirely","Luck alone, with no learnable component"],a:1},
   {q:"A personal wellness plan is most useful when it is...",o:["Created only after a crisis has already happened","Written in advance, while feeling well, so it's ready when needed","Never reviewed or updated","Kept identical to someone else's plan"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m17",n:17,title:"Mental Health Policies and Global Perspectives",mins:120,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"How mental health is addressed at a policy level worldwide, with a specific look at community-based care and the African context.",
  keyWords:["WHO","Sustainable Development Goals","mental health policy","community-based care"],
  sections:[
   {art:"global",h:"The WHO perspective and Sustainable Development Goals",p:[
    "The World Health Organization defines health as a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being, not merely the absence of disease — explicitly placing mental health on equal footing with physical health, and promotes access to mental health care as a fundamental part of universal health coverage.",
    "Mental health is also embedded in the United Nations' Sustainable Development Goals, particularly Goal 3 (good health and well-being), reflecting a global recognition that mental health is central to sustainable social and economic development, not a separate, lesser concern."]},
   {art:"culture",h:"Mental health in Africa",p:[
    "Mental health across Africa faces particular challenges: limited numbers of trained mental health professionals relative to population size, significant stigma in many communities, and historically low government health budgets allocated specifically to mental health services.",
    "At the same time, many African communities have strong traditions of communal support, extended family involvement, and, increasingly, growing investment in mental health awareness campaigns and training — building on existing community strength rather than only importing external models."]},
   {art:"agency",h:"National policies and community-based care",p:[
    "National mental health policies vary widely — some countries have comprehensive, well-funded mental health strategies integrated into primary healthcare, while others have minimal formal policy, leaving gaps that community and informal support networks often fill.",
    "Community-based mental health care — support delivered close to where people live, rather than only in centralised hospitals — is increasingly recognised as more accessible, less stigmatising, and often more effective than institution-only models, particularly in regions with limited specialist resources."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Look up whether your own country has a national mental health policy or strategy, and write two sentences on what you found (or on the fact that information was hard to find, which is itself informative).",
  check:[
   {q:"The WHO's definition of health explicitly includes...",o:["Only the absence of physical disease","Complete physical, mental and social well-being","Only physical fitness","Only freedom from infectious disease"],a:1},
   {q:"A particular challenge for mental health care in many African countries includes...",o:["An oversupply of trained mental health professionals","Limited numbers of trained professionals relative to population size, alongside stigma","Excessive government funding for mental health","No cultural traditions of community support at all"],a:1},
   {q:"Community-based mental health care is often considered advantageous because it is...",o:["Only available in large hospitals","More accessible and less stigmatising, especially where specialist resources are limited","Less effective than institution-only models in every case","Irrelevant to mental health outcomes"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"mh_m18",n:18,title:"Practical Activities and Case Studies",mins:120,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"Bringing the whole course together through reflection, real-world style case studies, and practical wellness planning exercises.",
  keyWords:["case studies","role play","group discussion","stress assessment","wellness planning"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"Self-reflection and case studies",p:[
    "Self-reflection means honestly reviewing your own patterns — stress triggers, coping habits, and support systems — using the concepts from earlier modules rather than treating this course as only about other people's mental health.",
    "Case studies help apply theory to realistic situations. For example: a university student, previously sociable, has stopped attending classes and messages friends less over several weeks, mentioning feeling 'tired all the time' — applying Module 4's warning signs and Module 10's support principles, a friend noticing this pattern could gently check in, listen without judgment, and encourage (not force) professional support."],
    ex:{t:"Example — working through a case study",b:["Situation: A coworker seems withdrawn and has missed several deadlines recently.","Applying this course: recognise possible warning signs (Module 4), approach with active listening (Module 10), and avoid dismissive language (Module 10's 'what not to say').","This structured approach turns course concepts into an actual, usable response."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Role plays and group discussions",p:[
    "Role plays — practising a supportive conversation out loud, even alone or with a friend — build real confidence for using active listening and ALGEE-style responses when a genuine situation arises, since rehearsed skills come more naturally under real pressure.",
    "Group discussions, whether in a classroom, workplace training, or community setting, allow different perspectives on the same scenario and often surface practical concerns (like 'what if they get upset with me for asking?') that reading alone wouldn't raise."],
  },
   {art:"measure",h:"Stress assessment tools and wellness planning",p:[
    "Simple stress assessment tools — rating your stress level from 1-10 across different areas of life (work, relationships, health, finances) — help identify where support or change is most needed, rather than treating stress as one vague, undifferentiated feeling.",
    "A wellness planning workshop brings together everything from this course into one concrete document: your personal warning signs, coping strategies, support contacts, and one or two specific goals for maintaining mental well-being going forward."],
  },
  ],
  activity:"Write a short case study of your own (real or realistic) involving someone showing early mental health warning signs, then write out, step by step, how you would apply this course's concepts to respond supportively.",
  check:[
   {q:"Applying course concepts to a case study mainly helps by...",o:["Replacing the need to learn the underlying concepts","Turning abstract concepts into a concrete, usable response for real situations","Making the material purely theoretical","Only being useful for professionals"],a:1},
   {q:"Practising a supportive conversation through role play mainly helps because...",o:["It guarantees a perfect response in every real situation","Rehearsed skills tend to come more naturally under real pressure","It replaces the need for genuine care","It's only useful in a classroom setting"],a:1},
   {q:"A simple stress assessment tool is useful because it...",o:["Treats stress as one vague, undifferentiated feeling","Identifies specific areas of life where support or change is most needed","Removes the need for any further action","Only applies to workplace stress"],a:1},
  ]},
];

